,"marks":1,"options":["Bacteria","Red blood cells","White blood cells","Squamous epithelial cells","Hyaline casts"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen examining unspun urine specimens under light microscopy:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacteria\u003C/strong\u003E are difficult to detect without centrifugation unless present in high concentrations (\u0026gt;100,000 colony forming units/mL)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERed blood cells\u003C/strong\u003E can be visualized and counted using a haemocytometer\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWhite blood cells\u003C/strong\u003E are visible and can be quantified\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESquamous epithelial cells\u003C/strong\u003E are large enough to be easily identified\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyaline casts\u003C/strong\u003E can be seen though may be easier to detect in centrifuged specimens\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECentrifugation of urine specimens concentrates cellular elements and increases detection sensitivity. Urine culture remains the gold standard for bacterial detection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Microscopic urinalysis can detect red blood cells, white blood cells, epithelial cells, casts, bacteria, and crystals.","Unspun urine examination has lower sensitivity than centrifuged specimens for detecting cellular elements.","Bacterial detection requires high-power microscopy and adequate bacterial concentrations (\u003E100,000 colony forming units/mL)."],"references":["Devill\u00e9 WL, Yzermans JC, van Duijn NP, Bezemer PD, van der Windt DA, Bouter LM. The urine dipstick test useful to rule out infections. A meta-analysis of the accuracy. BMC Urol. 2004 Jun 2;4:4. doi: 10.1186/1471-2490-4-4. PMID: 15175113; PMCID: PMC434513","Lim WH, Choi EK, Han KD, Rhee TM, Lee HJ, Lee SR, Kang SH, Cha MJ, Oh S. Proteinuria Detected by Urine Dipstick Test as a Risk Factor for Atrial Fibrillation: A Nationwide Population-Based Study. Sci Rep. 2017 Jul 24;7(1):6324. doi: 10.1038/s41598-017-06579-0. PMID: 28740259; PMCID: PMC5524798","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54761"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15142"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54761","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54761"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T19:10:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T19:13:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7830"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69308"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","pos